    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>If the following switching devices have similar power ratings, which one of them is the fastest?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p>SCR</p>"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<p>GTO</p>"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<p>IGBT</p>"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>Power MOSFET</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>When comparing the switching speeds of SCR (Silicon Controlled Rectifier), GTO (Gate Turn-Off Thyristor), IGBT (Insulated Gate Bipolar Transistor), and Power MOSFET (Metal-Oxide-Semiconductor Field-Effect Transistor), the key factor to consider is the intrinsic properties of these devices.</p>\n\n<p>1. <strong>SCR</strong>: Silicon Controlled Rectifiers are relatively slow in terms of switching speed. They are mainly used in applications where switching speed is not a critical factor, such as in power control and rectification.</p>\n\n<p>2. <strong>GTO</strong>: Gate Turn-Off Thyristors have better switching capabilities compared to SCRs, but they are still not the fastest due to the need for high gate current to turn off the device.</p>\n\n<p>3. <strong>IGBT</strong>: Insulated Gate Bipolar Transistors combine the characteristics of both MOSFETs and BJTs (Bipolar Junction Transistors). They offer faster switching speeds than SCRs and GTOs; however, they are not the fastest in this list.</p>\n\n<p>4. <strong>Power MOSFET</strong>: Power MOSFETs are known for their high-speed switching capabilities. They have a very high input impedance and low switching losses, making them the fastest amongst the options provided.</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the fastest switching device among the given options is the <strong>Power MOSFET</strong> (Option D).</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2024,
    "yearKey": "gate-ee-2024",
    "difficulty": null
  },
